    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Burton Lowell Baker was born April 2, 1912 in Fife Lake, Michigan. He received his initial college education at Kalamazoo College (A.B., 1933). Afterward he specialized in anatomical studies at Kansas State College (M.S., 1935) and Columbia University (Ph.D., 1941).</p>
      <p>Baker began his teaching career at Columbia, but taught there only briefly. Most of his teaching was done at the University of Michigan. He came to Ann Arbor as an instructor of anatomy in 1941. In 1945 he was named an assistant professor, in 1947 an associate professor, and in 1952 he became a full professor.</p>
      <p>Baker was constantly involved in research. Initially he was interested in cytology and the function of the parathyroid and adrenal glands, as well as the placenta. Later he investigated the local action of adrenocortical steroids and hormonal regulation of the gastrointestinal tract. His last projects concentrated upon the functional cytology of the pituitary gland and its regulation by the brain. His research led to the publication of over 110 papers.</p>
      <p>Baker served on a number of committees. Within the university he sat on various committees specializing in medical areas as well as committees dealing with broader subjects such as the Rackham School of Graduate Studies executive board; Advisory Committee on Appointments, Promotions and Titles in the Medical School; and the Medical School Executive Committee. Outside the university Baker served on important committees for both the American Cancer Society and the National Institute of Health.</p>
      <p>Baker was active in the university and academic communities when he died on October 14, 1978.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The papers which survive Dr. Baker reflect only the latter part of his life, primarily 1970 to 1978. They are arranged in a single Alphabetical Subject File. Most of the material is of a routine nature. Those research notes which remain are primarily drafts of published articles, often with a copy of the article and correspondence with the publisher filed with the research. The collection does include files from Dr. Burton's class in anatomy.</p>
    </scopecontent>
